          <div class="date" style="text-align:right;float:right;">6.14.2004</div><br /><br />
     
     
     <font class="TallRed">My day went great, thanks for asking.<a name="108727169027482739">&nbsp;</a></font>
		<div class="blackjustified" style="background-color:#eeeeee;padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;border-top:3px solid #cccccc;border-bottom:1px solid #333333;border-left:1px solid #cccccc;border-right:1px solid #cccccc;">
          There's something about working this job that seems a bit strange. While I don't know <i>everything</i> I think I should know at this point I still feel like I'm doin a pretty damn good job of adapting. I feel as if I have already been workin this job for a month and its not tiresome. I wake up @ 6am, shower, pick out something to wear and then I'm off on the metro. I'm like the rest of the sheep; not speaking, just moving and making wierd sounds-- out of our iPods and cellphone notifications.<br /><br />There's a definate pattern emerging already I see- and I can see how this would drive someone mad after 10 years. Everything in the city is so automatic that it almost forces you into an unbreakable loop, where your life plays before your eyes because the ground you stand on is actually a stair thats mechanically pushing you forward. "But what if I don't want to move forward?" somebody says. Well, you don't have that choice. You can walk backwards but you're just going to bump into a bunch of metro cowboys and if you refuse to take these automatic stairs you cannot leave at all. Just turn around and hop back on the train which will inevitably drop you off at another place just like the last with funky stairs awaiting.<br /><br />But I like automatic stairs.<br /><br />I suppose if it weren't for escalators the handicapped people would slow everybody down- and you can smell it here: time is money and its just burning away when we're all standing still. When you exit the metro you're greeted with new smells, new people, sounds, etc. Somebody is always trying to bum a dollar off of you. I have reached a dangerous point in my balances where I have taped up both my Credit/Debit cards and I am holding onto my metro card for dear life. I have more money on my metro card than I do in all of my accounts. I have decided to pack my lunch. Not only will this teach me discipline, but it will also give me better control over what I'm putting in my body. When you go out to a restaurant, they don't care how the meal is prepared as long as it tastes VERY GOOD then everything is okay. Thats why fat people think they're doin good by getting the lesser of the fattening buckets of grease but both are just as bad-- the only difference is the one you ordered has a splash of lettuce.<br /><br />Already, I find myself adapting to this new environment. I knew I would and that it was only a matter of time but I have only been here for approximately 5 days. I already know how to talk to people and how they will talk to me. There is one thing you don't need to bring up in a conversation @ D.C. and that's politics. You know why? Because the other person will.<br /><br />I was sitting in the park today watching the herds of people cross the street over and over again. An old man squabbles by, tips his hat to me, and plops down on the other side of the bench. He had shorts on, glasses just like my grandfather, and a loose black shirt. He seemed like a nice old man. That is, until he spoke. Thats when I came to the conclusion that I was speaking to an old dirty bastard.<blockquote>ODB: HUMID AS HELL, aint it?<br />Me: why yes *padding down fro* yes it sure seems to be.<br />Brain: Joe, it's 7:20 in the morning. WTF are you doing speaking to somebody at 7:20 in the morning?<br />ODB: Boy, you'd think after all the money they spent on this park they would get the shit straight, right?<br />[He points to the curb where it looks pretty good to me but then where it looks like it should continue, it suddenly stops.]<br />Me: It is a little incomplete, in my opinion.<br />ODB: Incomplete? It's fucked up man. They fucked up in this park. At least they have enough benches. God damn, how many people do they expect to sit down at once?<br />Me: I dunno. People don't look like they make a habit of sitting...<br />ODB: The hell they do. They sit all day.<br />[He then points to the middle of the park where there is a statue of a man, which is surrounded by small cannons.]<br />ODB: You know those are real fucking cannons?<br />Me: Really? No, I didn't know that.<br />ODB: Yup, they're (insert long military code-name)ers small little things but if they hit you...<br />Me: yeah...<br />ODB: They'd fuck you up.<br />Brain: Run. This dude is crazy. Pull his hat lid down over his eyes, and run like a little girl.<br />Joe: Well, I got to head in. Nice talkin' to ya.<br />ODB: Yeah Buddy, nice talkin to you too.</blockquote>And so it came at last, I made a new friend in the big city. <a href="http://www.yahoo.com">Yahoo!</a> Seriously though, if there are any E3R readers that live in the Ballston area of Arlington, <a href="mailto:e3rjb@msn.com">give me a holla</a>. I'm bored stiff.<br />
